3. Book-craft methodology (public domain craft literature)
======================================================================

book-forge implements established book-craft frameworks that long
predate both autonovel and authorclaw, and that are part of the open
craft literature. Attribution for these methods:

  - Save the Cat! Beat Sheet — Blake Snyder, "Save the Cat!" (2005)
  - Story Circle — Dan Harmon (channeling Joseph Campbell's
    Monomyth / Hero's Journey)
  - MICE Quotient — Orson Scott Card, "Characters and Viewpoint" (1988)
  - Sanderson's Laws of Magic — Brandon Sanderson (lecture series,
    beginning 2011)
  - Scene-Sequel Structure — Dwight V. Swain, "Techniques of the
    Selling Writer" (1965)
  - Romancing the Beat — Gwen Hayes, "Romancing the Beat" (2016)
  - The Three-Slider Character Model — Brandon Sanderson (lectures)
  - Wound / Want / Need / Lie framework — K.M. Weiland, "Creating
    Character Arcs" (2016)

These frameworks are referenced under fair use for the purpose of
teaching and tooling. Their names remain the trademarks of their
originators.

